{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":545,"text":"I grew up watching Star Trek. I love Star Trek."},{"time":4077,"text":"Star Trek made me want to see alien creatures,"},{"time":8539,"text":"creatures from a far-distant world."},{"time":10842,"text":"But basically, I figured out that I could find"},{"time":13629,"text":"those alien creatures right on Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":16606,"text":"And what I do is I study insects."},{"time":19259,"text":"I'm obsessed with insects, particularly insect flight."},{"time":22515,"text":"I think the evolution of insect flight is perhaps"},{"time":25656,"text":"one of the most important events in the history of life."},{"time":28398,"text":"Without insects, there'd be no flowering plants."},{"time":30635,"text":"Without flowering plants, there would be no"},{"time":32551,"text":"clever, fruit-eating primates giving TED Talks."}]},{"cues":[{"time":35688,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":37988,"text":"Now,"},{"time":39975,"text":"David and Hidehiko and Ketaki"},{"time":43014,"text":"gave a very compelling story about"},{"time":46459,"text":"the similarities between fruit flies and humans,"},{"time":49264,"text":"and there are many similarities,"},{"time":50753,"text":"and so you might think that if humans are similar to fruit flies,"},{"time":53755,"text":"the favorite behavior of a fruit fly might be this, for example --"},{"time":57552,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":59834,"text":"but in my talk, I don't want to emphasize on the similarities"},{"time":63025,"text":"between humans and fruit flies, but rather the differences,"},{"time":66092,"text":"and focus on the behaviors that I think fruit flies excel at doing."}]},{"cues":[{"time":71379,"text":"And so I want to show you a high-speed video sequence"},{"time":74235,"text":"of a fly shot at 7,000 frames per second in infrared lighting,"},{"time":78170,"text":"and to the right, off-screen, is an electronic looming predator"},{"time":82380,"text":"that is going to go at the fly."},{"time":83815,"text":"The fly is going to sense this predator."},{"time":85653,"text":"It is going to extend its legs out."},{"time":88108,"text":"It's going to sashay away"},{"time":89721,"text":"to live to fly another day."},{"time":92286,"text":"Now I have carefully cropped this sequence"},{"time":94648,"text":"to be exactly the duration of a human eye blink,"},{"time":97808,"text":"so in the time that it would take you to blink your eye,"},{"time":100642,"text":"the fly has seen this looming predator,"},{"time":103907,"text":"estimated its position, initiated a motor pattern to fly it away,"},{"time":110075,"text":"beating its wings at 220 times a second as it does so."},{"time":114539,"text":"I think this is a fascinating behavior"},{"time":116512,"text":"that shows how fast the fly's brain can process information."}]},{"cues":[{"time":120433,"text":"Now, flight -- what does it take to fly?"},{"time":123275,"text":"Well, in order to fly, just as in a human aircraft,"},{"time":126139,"text":"you need wings that can generate sufficient aerodynamic forces,"},{"time":128874,"text":"you need an engine sufficient to generate the power required for flight,"},{"time":132420,"text":"and you need a controller,"},{"time":134129,"text":"and in the first human aircraft, the controller was basically"},{"time":136755,"text":"the brain of Orville and Wilbur sitting in the cockpit."}]},{"cues":[{"time":141067,"text":"Now, how does this compare to a fly?"},{"time":143820,"text":"Well, I spent a lot of my early career trying to figure out"},{"time":147071,"text":"how insect wings generate enough force to keep the flies in the air."},{"time":151407,"text":"And you might have heard how engineers proved"},{"time":153017,"text":"that bumblebees couldn't fly."},{"time":155651,"text":"Well, the problem was in thinking that the insect wings"},{"time":158271,"text":"function in the way that aircraft wings work. But they don't."},{"time":161390,"text":"And we tackle this problem by building giant,"},{"time":164244,"text":"dynamically scaled model robot insects"},{"time":167676,"text":"that would flap in giant pools of mineral oil"},{"time":171012,"text":"where we could study the aerodynamic forces."},{"time":173286,"text":"And it turns out that the insects flap their wings"},{"time":175444,"text":"in a very clever way, at a very high angle of attack"},{"time":178036,"text":"that creates a structure at the leading edge of the wing,"},{"time":181157,"text":"a little tornado-like structure called a leading edge vortex,"},{"time":184356,"text":"and it's that vortex that actually enables the wings"},{"time":187310,"text":"to make enough force for the animal to stay in the air."},{"time":190669,"text":"But the thing that's actually most -- so, what's fascinating"},{"time":193097,"text":"is not so much that the wing has some interesting morphology."},{"time":196072,"text":"What's clever is the way the fly flaps it,"},{"time":199717,"text":"which of course ultimately is controlled by the nervous system,"},{"time":202853,"text":"and this is what enables flies to perform"},{"time":205500,"text":"these remarkable aerial maneuvers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":208307,"text":"Now, what about the engine?"},{"time":210404,"text":"The engine of the fly is absolutely fascinating."},{"time":212896,"text":"They have two types of flight muscle:"},{"time":214794,"text":"so-called power muscle, which is stretch-activated,"},{"time":217779,"text":"which means that it activates itself and does not need to be controlled"},{"time":221505,"text":"on a contraction-by-contraction basis by the nervous system."},{"time":224844,"text":"It's specialized to generate the enormous power required for flight,"},{"time":229453,"text":"and it fills the middle portion of the fly,"},{"time":231532,"text":"so when a fly hits your windshield,"},{"time":233079,"text":"it's basically the power muscle that you're looking at."},{"time":235485,"text":"But attached to the base of the wing"},{"time":237631,"text":"is a set of little, tiny control muscles"},{"time":240269,"text":"that are not very powerful at all, but they're very fast,"},{"time":243570,"text":"and they're able to reconfigure the hinge of the wing"},{"time":246776,"text":"on a stroke-by-stroke basis,"},{"time":248538,"text":"and this is what enables the fly to change its wing"},{"time":251680,"text":"and generate the changes in aerodynamic forces"},{"time":254651,"text":"which change its flight trajectory."},{"time":257224,"text":"And of course, the role of the nervous system is to control all this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":260787,"text":"So let's look at the controller."},{"time":262299,"text":"Now flies excel in the sorts of sensors"},{"time":264946,"text":"that they carry to this problem."},{"time":267230,"text":"They have antennae that sense odors and detect wind detection."},{"time":271357,"text":"They have a sophisticated eye which is"},{"time":273032,"text":"the fastest visual system on the planet."},{"time":275488,"text":"They have another set of eyes on the top of their head."},{"time":277524,"text":"We have no idea what they do."},{"time":279576,"text":"They have sensors on their wing."},{"time":282530,"text":"Their wing is covered with sensors, including sensors"},{"time":286290,"text":"that sense deformation of the wing."},{"time":288336,"text":"They can even taste with their wings."},{"time":290445,"text":"One of the most sophisticated sensors a fly has"},{"time":293000,"text":"is a structure called the halteres."},{"time":294807,"text":"The halteres are actually gyroscopes."},{"time":296686,"text":"These devices beat back and forth about 200 hertz during flight,"},{"time":301135,"text":"and the animal can use them to sense its body rotation"},{"time":303808,"text":"and initiate very, very fast corrective maneuvers."},{"time":307776,"text":"But all of this sensory information has to be processed"},{"time":310105,"text":"by a brain, and yes, indeed, flies have a brain,"},{"time":313825,"text":"a brain of about 100,000 neurons."}]},{"cues":[{"time":316984,"text":"Now several people at this conference"},{"time":319177,"text":"have already suggested that fruit flies could serve neuroscience"},{"time":323985,"text":"because they're a simple model of brain function."},{"time":327232,"text":"And the basic punchline of my talk is,"},{"time":329309,"text":"I'd like to turn that over on its head."},{"time":331967,"text":"I don't think they're a simple model of anything."},{"time":334595,"text":"And I think that flies are a great model."},{"time":337072,"text":"They're a great model for flies."},{"time":339588,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":342069,"text":"And let's explore this notion of simplicity."},{"time":345072,"text":"So I think, unfortunately, a lot of neuroscientists,"},{"time":347503,"text":"we're all somewhat narcissistic."},{"time":349335,"text":"When we think of brain, we of course imagine our own brain."},{"time":352768,"text":"But remember that this kind of brain,"},{"time":354728,"text":"which is much, much smaller"},{"time":356496,"text":"— instead of 100 billion neurons, it has 100,000 neurons —"},{"time":359174,"text":"but this is the most common form of brain on the planet"},{"time":362056,"text":"and has been for 400 million years."},{"time":364960,"text":"And is it fair to say that it's simple?"},{"time":367248,"text":"Well, it's simple in the sense that it has fewer neurons,"},{"time":369343,"text":"but is that a fair metric?"},{"time":371097,"text":"And I would propose it's not a fair metric."},{"time":373373,"text":"So let's sort of think about this. I think we have to compare --"},{"time":376473,"text":"(Laughter) —"},{"time":378032,"text":"we have to compare the size of the brain"},{"time":383153,"text":"with what the brain can do."},{"time":385183,"text":"So I propose we have a Trump number,"},{"time":388064,"text":"and the Trump number is the ratio of this man's"},{"time":390929,"text":"behavioral repertoire to the number of neurons in his brain."},{"time":394608,"text":"We'll calculate the Trump number for the fruit fly."},{"time":397276,"text":"Now, how many people here think the Trump number"},{"time":399960,"text":"is higher for the fruit fly?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":402449,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":404880,"text":"It's a very smart, smart audience."},{"time":408308,"text":"Yes, the inequality goes in this direction, or I would posit it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":411635,"text":"Now I realize that it is a little bit absurd"},{"time":414017,"text":"to compare the behavioral repertoire of a human to a fly."},{"time":417575,"text":"But let's take another animal just as an example. Here's a mouse."},{"time":421718,"text":"A mouse has about 1,000 times as many neurons as a fly."},{"time":426023,"text":"I used to study mice. When I studied mice,"},{"time":428050,"text":"I used to talk really slowly."},{"time":430887,"text":"And then something happened when I started to work on flies."},{"time":433463,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":435875,"text":"And I think if you compare the natural history of flies and mice,"},{"time":439335,"text":"it's really comparable. They have to forage for food."},{"time":442648,"text":"They have to engage in courtship."},{"time":445095,"text":"They have sex. They hide from predators."},{"time":448566,"text":"They do a lot of the similar things."},{"time":450546,"text":"But I would argue that flies do more."},{"time":452264,"text":"So for example, I'm going to show you a sequence,"},{"time":455642,"text":"and I have to say, some of my funding comes from the military,"},{"time":459847,"text":"so I'm showing this classified sequence"},{"time":461919,"text":"and you cannot discuss it outside of this room. Okay?"},{"time":466012,"text":"So I want you to look at the payload"},{"time":467920,"text":"at the tail of the fruit fly."},{"time":470946,"text":"Watch it very closely,"},{"time":473047,"text":"and you'll see why my six-year-old son"},{"time":477344,"text":"now wants to be a neuroscientist."},{"time":482073,"text":"Wait for it."},{"time":483252,"text":"Pshhew."},{"time":484821,"text":"So at least you'll admit that if fruit flies are not as clever as mice,"},{"time":487905,"text":"they're at least as clever as pigeons. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":492821,"text":"Now, I want to get across that it's not just a matter of numbers"},{"time":496788,"text":"but also the challenge for a fly to compute"},{"time":499386,"text":"everything its brain has to compute with such tiny neurons."},{"time":502235,"text":"So this is a beautiful image of a visual interneuron from a mouse"},{"time":505223,"text":"that came from Jeff Lichtman's lab,"},{"time":507991,"text":"and you can see the wonderful images of brains"},{"time":511238,"text":"that he showed in his talk."},{"time":514431,"text":"But up in the corner, in the right corner, you'll see,"},{"time":516799,"text":"at the same scale, a visual interneuron from a fly."},{"time":520911,"text":"And I'll expand this up."},{"time":522752,"text":"And it's a beautifully complex neuron."},{"time":524922,"text":"It's just very, very tiny, and there's lots of biophysical challenges"},{"time":528407,"text":"with trying to compute information with tiny, tiny neurons."}]},{"cues":[{"time":532030,"text":"How small can neurons get? Well, look at this interesting insect."},{"time":535567,"text":"It looks sort of like a fly. It has wings, it has eyes,"},{"time":537779,"text":"it has antennae, its legs, complicated life history,"},{"time":540578,"text":"it's a parasite, it has to fly around and find caterpillars"},{"time":543674,"text":"to parasatize,"},{"time":545056,"text":"but not only is its brain the size of a salt grain,"},{"time":549171,"text":"which is comparable for a fruit fly,"},{"time":551140,"text":"it is the size of a salt grain."},{"time":554066,"text":"So here's some other organisms at the similar scale."},{"time":557701,"text":"This animal is the size of a paramecium and an amoeba,"},{"time":561831,"text":"and it has a brain of 7,000 neurons that's so small --"},{"time":565711,"text":"you know these things called cell bodies you've been hearing about,"},{"time":568167,"text":"where the nucleus of the neuron is?"},{"time":569818,"text":"This animal gets rid of them because they take up too much space."},{"time":573278,"text":"So this is a session on frontiers in neuroscience."},{"time":575751,"text":"I would posit that one frontier in neuroscience is to figure out how the brain of that thing works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":581111,"text":"But let's think about this. How can you make a small number of neurons do a lot?"},{"time":586744,"text":"And I think, from an engineering perspective,"},{"time":589266,"text":"you think of multiplexing."},{"time":590995,"text":"You can take a hardware and have that hardware"},{"time":593698,"text":"do different things at different times,"},{"time":595311,"text":"or have different parts of the hardware doing different things."},{"time":598306,"text":"And these are the two concepts I'd like to explore."},{"time":601577,"text":"And they're not concepts that I've come up with,"},{"time":603235,"text":"but concepts that have been proposed by others in the past."}]},{"cues":[{"time":607780,"text":"And one idea comes from lessons from chewing crabs."},{"time":610855,"text":"And I don't mean chewing the crabs."},{"time":612722,"text":"I grew up in Baltimore, and I chew crabs very, very well."},{"time":616321,"text":"But I'm talking about the crabs actually doing the chewing."},{"time":619178,"text":"Crab chewing is actually really fascinating."},{"time":621208,"text":"Crabs have this complicated structure under their carapace"},{"time":624467,"text":"called the gastric mill"},{"time":625777,"text":"that grinds their food in a variety of different ways."},{"time":628207,"text":"And here's an endoscopic movie of this structure."},{"time":633466,"text":"The amazing thing about this is that it's controlled"},{"time":636026,"text":"by a really tiny set of neurons, about two dozen neurons"},{"time":639458,"text":"that can produce a vast variety of different motor patterns,"},{"time":644421,"text":"and the reason it can do this is that this little tiny ganglion"},{"time":648768,"text":"in the crab is actually inundated by many, many neuromodulators."},{"time":652952,"text":"You heard about neuromodulators earlier."},{"time":655093,"text":"There are more neuromodulators"},{"time":657318,"text":"that alter, that innervate this structure than actually neurons in the structure,"},{"time":662803,"text":"and they're able to generate a complicated set of patterns."},{"time":667045,"text":"And this is the work by Eve Marder and her many colleagues"},{"time":670486,"text":"who've been studying this fascinating system"},{"time":672781,"text":"that show how a smaller cluster of neurons"},{"time":674933,"text":"can do many, many, many things"},{"time":676758,"text":"because of neuromodulation that can take place on a moment-by-moment basis."},{"time":681614,"text":"So this is basically multiplexing in time."},{"time":684053,"text":"Imagine a network of neurons with one neuromodulator."},{"time":686838,"text":"You select one set of cells to perform one sort of behavior,"},{"time":690316,"text":"another neuromodulator, another set of cells,"},{"time":692934,"text":"a different pattern, and you can imagine"},{"time":694647,"text":"you could extrapolate to a very, very complicated system."}]},{"cues":[{"time":698525,"text":"Is there any evidence that flies do this?"},{"time":700619,"text":"Well, for many years in my laboratory and other laboratories around the world,"},{"time":703994,"text":"we've been studying fly behaviors in little flight simulators."},{"time":706642,"text":"You can tether a fly to a little stick."},{"time":708348,"text":"You can measure the aerodynamic forces it's creating."},{"time":710849,"text":"You can let the fly play a little video game"},{"time":713395,"text":"by letting it fly around in a visual display."},{"time":717273,"text":"So let me show you a little tiny sequence of this."},{"time":719610,"text":"Here's a fly"},{"time":720837,"text":"and a large infrared view of the fly in the flight simulator,"},{"time":724274,"text":"and this is a game the flies love to play."},{"time":726229,"text":"You allow them to steer towards the little stripe,"},{"time":728666,"text":"and they'll just steer towards that stripe forever."},{"time":731491,"text":"It's part of their visual guidance system."},{"time":735049,"text":"But very, very recently, it's been possible"},{"time":737394,"text":"to modify these sorts of behavioral arenas for physiologies."},{"time":742334,"text":"So this is the preparation that one of my former post-docs,"},{"time":744822,"text":"Gaby Maimon, who's now at Rockefeller, developed,"},{"time":747265,"text":"and it's basically a flight simulator"},{"time":748951,"text":"but under conditions where you actually can stick an electrode"},{"time":752026,"text":"in the brain of the fly and record"},{"time":754290,"text":"from a genetically identified neuron in the fly's brain."},{"time":757946,"text":"And this is what one of these experiments looks like."},{"time":760244,"text":"It was a sequence taken from another post-doc in the lab,"},{"time":763215,"text":"Bettina Schnell."},{"time":764414,"text":"The green trace at the bottom is the membrane potential"},{"time":767806,"text":"of a neuron in the fly's brain,"},{"time":769836,"text":"and you'll see the fly start to fly, and the fly is actually"},{"time":772778,"text":"controlling the rotation of that visual pattern itself"},{"time":776057,"text":"by its own wing motion,"},{"time":777536,"text":"and you can see this visual interneuron"},{"time":779646,"text":"respond to the pattern of wing motion as the fly flies."},{"time":783554,"text":"So for the first time we've actually been able to record"},{"time":785930,"text":"from neurons in the fly's brain while the fly"},{"time":788838,"text":"is performing sophisticated behaviors such as flight."},{"time":793306,"text":"And one of the lessons we've been learning"},{"time":795161,"text":"is that the physiology of cells that we've been studying"},{"time":797581,"text":"for many years in quiescent flies"},{"time":800002,"text":"is not the same as the physiology of those cells"},{"time":802650,"text":"when the flies actually engage in active behaviors"},{"time":805386,"text":"like flying and walking and so forth."},{"time":807925,"text":"And why is the physiology different?"},{"time":810850,"text":"Well it turns out it's these neuromodulators,"},{"time":812907,"text":"just like the neuromodulators in that little tiny ganglion in the crabs."},{"time":816858,"text":"So here's a picture of the octopamine system."},{"time":819408,"text":"Octopamine is a neuromodulator"},{"time":821162,"text":"that seems to play an important role in flight and other behaviors."},{"time":825498,"text":"But this is just one of many neuromodulators"},{"time":827970,"text":"that's in the fly's brain."},{"time":829041,"text":"So I really think that, as we learn more,"},{"time":831707,"text":"it's going to turn out that the whole fly brain"},{"time":834234,"text":"is just like a large version of this stomatogastric ganglion,"},{"time":837323,"text":"and that's one of the reasons why it can do so much with so few neurons."}]},{"cues":[{"time":841683,"text":"Now, another idea, another way of multiplexing"},{"time":844470,"text":"is multiplexing in space,"},{"time":846126,"text":"having different parts of a neuron"},{"time":847820,"text":"do different things at the same time."},{"time":849942,"text":"So here's two sort of canonical neurons"},{"time":851775,"text":"from a vertebrate and an invertebrate,"},{"time":854060,"text":"a human pyramidal neuron from Ramon y Cajal,"},{"time":857310,"text":"and another cell to the right, a non-spiking interneuron,"},{"time":861313,"text":"and this is the work of Alan Watson and Malcolm Burrows many years ago,"},{"time":865460,"text":"and Malcolm Burrows came up with a pretty interesting idea"},{"time":868535,"text":"based on the fact that this neuron from a locust"},{"time":871417,"text":"does not fire action potentials."},{"time":873376,"text":"It's a non-spiking cell."},{"time":875124,"text":"So a typical cell, like the neurons in our brain,"},{"time":877904,"text":"has a region called the dendrites that receives input,"},{"time":880656,"text":"and that input sums together"},{"time":883245,"text":"and will produce action potentials"},{"time":885541,"text":"that run down the axon and then activate"},{"time":887872,"text":"all the output regions of the neuron."},{"time":890168,"text":"But non-spiking neurons are actually quite complicated"},{"time":893044,"text":"because they can have input synapses and output synapses"},{"time":896156,"text":"all interdigitated, and there's no single action potential"},{"time":899819,"text":"that drives all the outputs at the same time."},{"time":902945,"text":"So there's a possibility that you have computational compartments"},{"time":906852,"text":"that allow the different parts of the neuron"},{"time":910830,"text":"to do different things at the same time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":913390,"text":"So these basic concepts of multitasking in time"},{"time":918061,"text":"and multitasking in space,"},{"time":920422,"text":"I think these are things that are true in our brains as well,"},{"time":923254,"text":"but I think the insects are the true masters of this."},{"time":925831,"text":"So I hope you think of insects a little bit differently next time,"},{"time":928947,"text":"and as I say up here, please think before you swat."}]},{"cues":[{"time":931882,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}